Paragraph 1: "So there's a running story about Andreessen Horowitz basically saying people in big tech companies are not doing enough real work to justify their existence..." That's fine.

"And while this might seem to an unwarranted assault on the work ethic of tech workers (who I'm sure are mostly diligent and hardworking), I can't help but agree that he's probably onto something, at least from the capitalist perspective."

Issue: "might seem to an unwarranted assault" should be "might seem like an unwarranted assault" or "might seem to be an unwarranted assault". So grammar: missing article or preposition.

Also "he's probably onto something" - "he" refers to Andreessen Horowitz (a firm) but it's okay.

Paragraph 2: "In fact, back when tech stocks were down last year, I briefly wondered whether it would be a good idea to buy some at the relatively low prices -- in particular META and GOOG. My analysis back then was exactly on the same line of logic -- while META and GOOG (and particularly GOOG) don't seem to be capable of creating new products and finding new avenues of growth, it seems their monopolies are still functional and they can probably squeeze quite a bit of profit from the monopolies before things break down."

Potential issues: "My analysis back then was exactly on the same line of logic" - awkward but maybe stylistic. "exactly on the same line of logic" maybe grammar: should be "exactly along the same line of logic" or "exactly the same line of logic". Could be considered grammar.

Also "it seems their monopolies are still functional and they can probably squeeze quite a bit of profit from the monopolies before things break down." "their monopolies" plural but "they" refers to companies; okay.

Next: "That, and when shareholders are unhappy, they can always layoff more people to reduce costs and increase margins and profit, and I had no ounce of doubt that they can cut costs by almost half without really affecting day to day operations."

Issues: "layoff" should be "lay off" (verb) or "layoffs" as noun. Also "layoff more people" is wrong; should be "lay off more people". Also "I had no ounce of doubt that they can cut costs" - tense mismatch: past "had" vs present "can". Should be "could cut". Also "day to day" should be hyphenated "day-to-day". Also "they can cut costs by almost half without really affecting day to day operations." Might be okay but tense.

Next: "And as we've seen with their (GOOG mainly) first round of layoffs in early 2023, McKinsey Pichai is definitely ready to do whatever pleases the shareholders in this regard."

Issue: "McKinsey Pichai" is wrong; should be "Sundar Pichai". Also "McKinsey" is a consulting firm; maybe a typo. Also "their (GOOG mainly)" parentheses weird. Also "first round of layoffs in early 2023" okay.

Next: "In the end I didn't make any trades, if only because I would have hated how I participated and enabled this kind of predatory capitalist attitude -- but ideological concerns aside, the logic is solid."

Potential: "if only because" maybe okay. "I would have hated how I participated and enabled" - tense: conditional perfect vs past? Might be okay.

"The only risk is basically regulatory (antitrust), but In America We Trust they're capitalist enough to not kill their golden goose."

Issues: Capitalization: "In America We Trust" should be lowercase except maybe "In God We Trust"? Actually phrase "In America We Trust" is a play on "In God We Trust". Should be "In America, we trust" maybe. Also "they're capitalist enough to not kill their golden goose." "they're" refers to America? ambiguous.

Next: "(There's also a concern whether the companies will remain healthy enough for investors (as a whole) to recoup their capital investments before the companies crash and burn... I'm not sure I can accurately predict what GOOG will be like in say 15 years -- tech companies can fail REALLY fast once there's a paradigm shift.)"

Issues: "concern whether" should be "concern that" or "concern about whether". Also "in say 15 years" maybe okay but could be "in, say, 15 years". Also "REALLY" caps.

Next: "With interest rates still held "high", the free money is draining away, and with promises of revolutionary tech largely gone (besides small pockets of AI, which in practice currently is operationally much smaller than general tech), the ruthless capitalist engine is taking over to ensure financial "efficiency".  This necessarily involves layoffs and wage cuts/stagnation until the labor supply/demand reaches equilibrium (i.e. these jobs are going to be as great/shitty as any random gig in the general job market), and product enshittification until antitrust slams down hard."

Issues: "held "high"" quotes weird. Maybe "held high". Also "wage cuts/stagnation" maybe okay. "product enshittification" is a neologism but maybe stylistic. "until antitrust slams down hard." "slams down" maybe okay but could be "slams down" is informal.

Next: "Those who read history knows -- every industry goes through this phrase in some form or another."

Issues: Subject-verb agreement: "Those who read history knows" should be "know". Also "this phrase" should be "this phase". So grammar.

Next: "Abundance in isolated, privileged pockets isn't True Abundance."

